  {
    "speaker": "interviewee",
    "tag": "LH",
    "text": "This is a three-zone pass, which we obtained in Prague, Czechoslovakia. It took weeks and weeks to get it, and we had to-- Bernard had to bribe people with vodka and don't know what else. And this pass enabled us to leave Prague finally, and move on to Germany to look for survivors, for family. [PAUSES FOR 47 SECONDS] This is the first letter I received from my sister Hildegard from Jerusalem in August of 1945. I had written a short notice to the Red Cross saying that I was alive and that the fate of my mother and brother, Wolfgang, were unknown. My father had died, and Selly had died. This is a response to my letter, and she wanted very much that I would come to Israel, and was trying to do all she could. When I received this letter, I became totally unglued. To see my sister's handwriting, to know that I wasn't alone, there was another member of my family. I didn't know of her whereabouts then. I didn't know if she had made it into Israel or if the boat had gotten through. And this was a confirmation of it. And from then on, we were able to correspond and get all the details. [PAUSES FOR 8 SECONDS]",
